<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  JustDownload Windows bootstrapper (TASK-159, AC0). Built with the same pinned WiX Toolset v5 CLI as
  Product.wxs (build-time-only tooling, MS-RL, see Product.wxs's header and the TASK-076 notes).

  Why this exists: JustDownload.App ships framework-dependent (docs/publishing.md) — it needs the shared
  .NET 8 Desktop Runtime already on the machine. Before this task, `JustDownload-win-x64.msi` installed
  fine on a runtime-less machine and then silently failed to launch (missing hostfxr). This Burn bundle
  ("JustDownload-win-x64-Setup.exe") wraps that same MSI with a chained install of the Microsoft .NET 8
  Desktop Runtime, so the user is prompted/shown progress instead of hitting a silent failure. The plain
  MSI is still built and still works standalone for anyone who already has the runtime and wants the
  smaller, always-elevation-free per-user install (see the elevation note below) — this bundle is the
  new recommended default entry point, not a replacement artifact.

  Runtime package (ExePackage "DotNetDesktopRuntime"):
  - Pinned to a specific, immutable Microsoft CDN URL for one exact patch release, NOT the "latest"
    aka.ms redirector — a concrete per-version URL under builds.dotnet.microsoft.com never changes its
    bytes once published, so Hash/Size/Version below stay valid forever (mirrors the ffmpeg manifest's
    "pin by hash to an immutable release" approach in JustDownload.Core/Media/FfmpegManifest.cs).
    Any 8.0.x runtime satisfies our app (net8.0 TFM, default rollForward=Minor rolls forward within
    major 8) — installing exactly this patch (or the installer no-op'ing because something newer is
    already present) is sufficient; we do not need "the very latest" patch.
  - Hash/Size/Version were generated straight from the downloaded file with the WiX CLI's own tool:
      wix burn remotepayload -du <DownloadUrl> -packagetype exe <local-copy-of-the-exe>
    To move to a newer .NET 8 patch: download the new windowsdesktop-runtime-8.0.<x>-win-x64.exe from
    https://builds.dotnet.microsoft.com/dotnet/WindowsDesktop/8.0.<x>/, re-run the command above against
    it, and paste the regenerated Name/ProductName/Description/DownloadUrl/Hash/Size/Version below.
  - No <ExePackage DetectCondition>: investigated and rejected two ways to pre-detect "is a satisfying
    .NET 8 Desktop Runtime already installed" at Burn Detect-time (before elevation) so the download/
    install could be skipped when unnecessary:
      1. util:RegistrySearch against the real on-disk key this task verified on a live 8.0-runtime
         machine, HKLM\SOFTWARE\WOW6432Node\dotnet\Setup\InstalledVersions\x64\sharedfx\
         Microsoft.WindowsDesktop.App\<version> — every installed version is its own child key
         (e.g. "8.0.22"), and RegistrySearch can only test one exact, fully-known key path; WiX v5 has
         no wildcard/"does any 8.0.* subkey exist" search primitive, so this would mean hardcoding and
         forever maintaining one RegistrySearch per historical patch release — exactly the "unreasonable
         bespoke" case CLAUDE.md's simplicity rule and this task's own guidance say to avoid.
      2. util:ProductSearch/MsiPackage UpgradeCode family detection — rejected after downloading and
         inspecting two real Microsoft Windows Desktop Runtime x64 MSIs (8.0.0 and 8.0.28) with the
         Windows Installer COM API: their UpgradeCodes differ between patch releases
         ({D2455C43-5229-6E82-20B0-B108989248C2} vs {EC3BD7E4-53DA-5786-BBE0-ED5AD3FF7148}), so a single
         pinned UpgradeCode cannot reliably detect "any 8.0.x is present" either.
    Given both Burn-native detection routes are genuinely unreliable for a rolling target like the .NET
    runtime, this package is chained unconditionally instead: Microsoft's own runtime installer performs
    accurate detection internally and exits quickly without reinstalling when an equal-or-newer version
    is already present (the standard, documented behaviour their installer is built for, and the same
    pattern most Burn bundles use to chain redistributables like the VC++ runtime). Net effect: never a
    silent "installed but won't launch" outcome, at the cost of always running (briefly) even when the
    runtime turns out to already be there.
  - Cache="remove": don't keep a second local copy of the ~55 MB runtime installer in the package cache
    after it runs — Permanent="yes"/no UninstallArguments means our bundle will never invoke it again to
    uninstall the shared runtime (other apps may still need it), so there is nothing to keep it around
    for. Matches the "light by default" budget (K3).
  - Elevation note: the .NET Desktop Runtime installer is only ever per-machine (Microsoft doesn't offer
    a per-user runtime) and its own embedded manifest requests admin, so Windows shows a UAC prompt the
    moment this bundle launches it — confirmed by extracting this bundle's own Burn manifest
    (`wix burn extract`), which reports `PerMachine="no"` for the bundle/engine itself (it does not need
    to pre-elevate) while the child runtime installer still triggers its own OS-level elevation prompt
    when it runs. The MSI step that follows stays per-user (D8) with no further prompt. Net effect: one
    UAC prompt appears on every run of this bootstrapper (see the DetectCondition note above), even when
    the runtime turns out to already be present — a known, deliberate trade-off of AC0, not an oversight.
    Anyone who already has the runtime and wants a guaranteed no-UAC install can still use the plain
    JustDownload-win-x64.msi directly.

  App package (MsiPackage): the existing per-user Product.wxs output, embedded/compressed into this
  bundle (not a separate download) so installing the app itself needs no extra network round-trip beyond
  fetching this one file.
-->
<Wix xmlns="http://wixtoolset.org/schemas/v4/wxs"
     xmlns:bal="http://wixtoolset.org/schemas/v4/wxs/bal">
  <Bundle Name="JustDownload Setup"
          Manufacturer="JustDownload"
          Version="$(var.ProductVersion)"
          UpgradeCode="a3a1a9a1-7c0a-4f6b-9a9e-7f3d9a6f9b5a">

    <BootstrapperApplication>
      <bal:WixStandardBootstrapperApplication Theme="rtfLicense" LicenseFile="$(var.InstallerDir)\License.rtf" />
    </BootstrapperApplication>

    <Chain>
      <ExePackage Id="DotNetDesktopRuntime"
                  DisplayName="Microsoft .NET 8 Desktop Runtime"
                  InstallArguments="/install /quiet /norestart"
                  Permanent="yes"
                  Vital="yes"
                  Cache="remove">
        <ExePackagePayload Name="windowsdesktop-runtime-8.0.28-win-x64.exe"
                            ProductName="Microsoft Windows Desktop Runtime - 8.0.28 (x64)"
                            Description="Microsoft Windows Desktop Runtime - 8.0.28 (x64)"
                            DownloadUrl="https://builds.dotnet.microsoft.com/dotnet/WindowsDesktop/8.0.28/windowsdesktop-runtime-8.0.28-win-x64.exe"
                            Hash="931E5463994AE1D4984BCC05BAF940979511185EC1A9BCA0A5C0E5963D290FBFE3B348E5BD804FECBE698669374A34CEE20E6D1E220E275E1536D55C848FC068"
                            Size="58246192"
                            Version="8.0.28.36119" />
      </ExePackage>

      <MsiPackage SourceFile="$(var.MsiPath)" Vital="yes" />
    </Chain>
  </Bundle>
</Wix>
